        Running a dedicated <strong>monitor refresh rate test</strong> ensures that your hardware is configured correctly. It is surprisingly common for users to purchase high-end gaming monitors (such as 144Hz, 240Hz, or 360Hz models) but leave them capped at a default 60Hz setting in their operating system's advanced display properties. With this web-based <strong>refresh rate test monitor</strong> analyzer, you can quickly verify if your setup matches your hardware's maximum potential. Furthermore, running a <strong>screen refresh rate test</strong> helps identify stutter, GPU rendering limitations, or browser-specific compositor issues that prevent fluid visual pacing. By performing a quick diagnostic, you can rule out cable bottlenecks (like outdated HDMI standards) or software misconfigurations that limit your screen's performance.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        How the Display Refresh Rate Test Works
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        To deliver high-precision results, our tool utilizes the HTML5 <code>requestAnimationFrame</code> API to sync with the browserâ€™s repaint cycle. The tool records the millisecond timestamp of each draw callback and computes the frame-to-frame delay. By collecting these samples, our <strong>display refresh rate test</strong> calculates both the median delay and the stability (standard deviation) of the loop. To screen out occasional OS background hiccups or CPU spike stutters, the analyzer ignores statistical outliers and displays a clean, stabilized estimation of your screen's actual Hertz rating. This gives you a more realistic representation of real-world frame consistency compared to basic counters that simply divide total frames by seconds.
      </p>

